derstand human behavior from an evolutionary perspective. To that end, The Hadza also articulates the necessary background for readers whose exposure to human evolutionary theory is minimal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHatsa (African people)xFood. 0aHatsa (African people)xHunting. 0aHatsa (African people)xSocial life and customs. 0aHunting and gathering societieszTanzania. 0aSocial ecologyzTanzania. 0aSocial evolutionzTanzania. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094544940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945449423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520945449/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles